        <h1>Hill Billy Tesla</h1>
        <h5>My first large scale embedded systems project.</h5>
        <p>
            This project was created during my senior year in highschool at a technical school -- Buckeye Career Center. 
            The project began with a base RC car. From there, I hooked up an after market ESC and burnt through 2 servos trying to figure out how to control them.
            The first prototype was simply a plastic sheet mounted on the car to mount sensors to the car. Originally, that car was designed with
            2 Lidar and 3 super sonic sensors. After realizing I didn't have time to work with Kalman Filtering, I went with a GPS and Magnetometer instead.
            After some time I finally got the car to steer and move. The first script made to control the car was simply making it face towards north using the magnetometer.
            Most of the time spent in the first month of this car was simply trying to get the car to move and the sensors to work. I tried 4 differnt brands of GPS until I finally got a 300 dollar U-Blox GNSS.
            After that, development was rapid, a friend of mine designed the 3D printed body for it so it looked cool and could mount sensors. The windshield was actually an LCD. The wiring was beginning to get complicated 
            and I was running out of ports on the Arduino Mega so I learned how to design PCB's and ordered a few. I found out that the magnetometer wasn't accurate enough so I ordered a adafruit IMU which made a world of difference. The day before the competition (1 months and around 3 weeks in) I had the car run properly for the first time.
            I didn't sleep for two days straight to make sure the car was competition ready. At the competition, I accidentally shorted the battery which destroyed the GNSS and IMU. I worked for hours to get it working again but did not realise the IMU was broken which caused me to perform poorly at the competition.
            After the competition, I worked to refine that car mechanically, programatically, and asthetically. Eventually the Digital Electronics competition came up and I won. The project totalled 600 hours over 2 months or on average 10 hours per day.  
        </p>

